content:
To merge cells in a LaTeX table, you can use the `\multirow` and `\multicolumn` commands provided by the `multirow` package. Here's how you can modify your code to achieve the desired merged cells:

```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{multirow}

\begin{document}

\begin{tabular}{|c|c|c|}
\hline
\multirow{2}{*}{A} & 2 & 3 \\ \cline{2-3}
                    & 5 & 6 \\ \hline
7 & \multicolumn{2}{c|}{B} \\ \hline
\end{tabular}

\end{document}
```

### Explanation:

1. **Merging Cells (1,1) and (2,1):**
   - Use `\multirow{2}{*}{A}` to merge the first two rows of the first column, placing the text "A" in the merged cell.
   - The `\cline{2-3}` command is used to draw horizontal lines only under columns 2 and 3, since column 1 is merged vertically and doesn't need a horizontal line under it for the first row.

2. **Merging Cells (3,1) and (3,2):**
   - Use `\multicolumn{2}{c|}{B}` to merge the first and second columns of the third row, placing the text "B" in the merged cell.
   - The `c|` in the `\multicolumn` command specifies that the content in the merged cell should be centered, and there should be a vertical line on the right side of the merged cell.

With these changes, your table will have the desired merged cells with the specified text.
